<<r sim_params, include=FALSE>>=
n <- 1000000L
sd_info <- 0.2
sd_obf <- 0.3
sd_epsilon <- 0.1
sd_nu <- 0 # 0.4
delta_1 <- 0.5
phi_1 <- 0.1 # 0.25
phi_2 <- 0.42
@

\section{Simulation}

To check the math above, I simulate some data ($\Sexpr{prettyNum(n)}$ observations) assuming $\sigma_I= \Sexpr{sd_info}$, $\sigma_O= \Sexpr{sd_obf}$, 
 $\sigma_{\epsilon}= \Sexpr{sd_epsilon}$, $\sigma_{\nu}= \Sexpr{sd_nu}$, $\varphi_1= \Sexpr{phi_1}$, $\varphi_2=\Sexpr{phi_2}$, and $\delta_1=\Sexpr{delta_1}$.
I generate all underlying random variables (i.e., $\textit{InfoNoObf}$, $\textit{Obf}$, $\nu$, and $\epsilon$) as mean-zero, normally distributed, independent variables.

<<r sim_run, include=FALSE, dependson="sim_params", cache=TRUE>>=
info <- rnorm(n, sd=sd_info)
obf <- rnorm(n, sd=sd_obf)
epsilon <- rnorm(n, sd=sd_epsilon)
nu <- rnorm(n, sd=sd_nu)

y <- info * phi_1 + obf * phi_2 + epsilon
x <- info * delta_1 + nu

fm <- lm(y ~ x)
y_fitted <- predict(fm)

coef_expected <- (phi_1 * delta_1 * sd_info^2)/(delta_1^2 * sd_info^2 + sd_nu^2)
coef_expected

# coef_expected_y_hat <- 

@

The expected coefficient is \Sexpr{round(coef_expected, digits=4)} and the actual coefficient is \Sexpr{round(fm$coefficients['x'], digits=4)}.

Note that $y - \hat{y}$ is correlated with \textit{InfoNoObf} ($\rho = \Sexpr{round(cor(y-y_fitted, info), digits=4)}$), and $\hat{y}$ is correlated with \textit{InfoNoObf} ($\rho = \Sexpr{round(cor(y_fitted, info), digits=4)}$), even though $\hat{y}$ is uncorrelated with $y - \hat{y}$ ($\rho = \Sexpr{round(cor(y-y_fitted, y_fitted), digits=4)}$)

